==English==

===Etymology===
Refers to the idea that [[w:Newcastle|Newcastle]] was once a major producer of [[coal]].

===Verb===
'''to [[carry]] [[coals]] [[to]] [[Newcastle]]'''

#{{idiom}} To do something that is not [[needed]] or [[redundant]].
#:'''1851''' ''However curious it may seem for an oil-ship to be borrowing oil on the whale-ground, and however much it may invertedly contradict the old proverb about '''carrying coals to Newcastle''', yet sometimes such a thing really happens; and in the present case Captain Derick De Deer did indubitably conduct a lamp-feeder as Flask did declare.'' — Herman Melville, ''Moby Dick'', [http://etext.virginia.edu/etcbin/ot2www-pubeng?specfile=/texts/english/modeng/publicsearch/modengpub.o2w&act=text&offset=471550395&textreg=2&query=coals+to+Newcastle&id=eaf642 Chapter 81.]

